segments.text: School education, and we're going to get to A&M today.
Tell me about your grade school education.
Well, it was all at Wheelock up through the 10th grade.
I'm sorry, through the 9th grade.
The little rural school at Wheelock was considered a very good rural school.
And I started in the first grade and went through the ninth grade.
And at the time I graduated from the ninth grade, the 10th and 11th grade were transported to Franklin.
That was a change in the program.
Prior to that time, you could go to 10 grades at Wheelock.
and then you had to go to Hearn or Franklin or Bryan or somewhere to get your 11th grade.
It was not an accredited full high school.
But at the time, exactly the time I graduated from the 9th grade, they started transporting to Franklin by bus.
So I went to Franklin High School my 10th and 11th years and graduated.
The years at Wheelock were, looking back on them now, very interesting.
It was a...
In what way?
Oh, enjoyable from the standpoint of we had lots of competitive sports.
We had some very, very fine rural teachers.
I look back and wonder how in the world they ever put up with all that bunch of people, but
Our lower grades of education were, I don't know, just fascinating, really.
I guess kiddos at that age really don't know what to appreciate, but looking back on it, I think we were very fortunate in the type of school we had in the rural community.
How large was it?
I'd like to make some sort of an estimate.
The grades, of course, as they got further up, there were less in the grades, but I would imagine there were some... Oh, I would suspect there were 150.
150 students in the entire school?
That would be my guess.
How large was in your graduating class?
See, I graduated from Franklin.
Oh yeah, which was how large, okay, how large was it?
Franklin was a pretty big school because they had, they brought everybody in the whole, that part of the county.
I imagine they were 60 or 70 in the graduating class at Franklin.
Now our ninth grade class that would have graduated in Wheelock probably had like 10 or 15, relatively small.
In the elementary school, what were your favorite subjects?
Well, I always got some fascination out of math.
Math gave me no problem, really.
I had less, I guess, fascination in English and the various grammars and this sort of thing.
And we really didn't have much of the sciences in that little rural school.
I didn't even get a chance to take chemistry in high school.
So really ours were all just the basic courses.
But I enjoyed my math always.
And you enjoyed it when you got into high school too then?
That's correct.
That was your favorite subject?
All right, I'm sure it was.
I didn't, I found no difficulty in the math courses.
In fact, it's a really interesting thing, and this goes back to a little interesting aspect, too.
My wife and I started in the first grade together.
Oh, really?
She's from Poso.
She's born in Puso.

We didn't really call ourselves sweethearts until we got up in probably seventh or eighth grade, but after we got into high school, of course her favorite subjects were English and grammar and Macbeth and all those things, and she'd have difficulty with her math.
I'd help her with her math, she'd help me with English.
So, yeah, but math was no problem for me.
Geometry, trigonometry, all those things.
And you had trigonometry in high school then?
No.
But you had algebra?
Did you have algebra?
We had algebra, too.
I guess algebra one and two, probably.
I don't think we had.
We had geometry in high school, I believe.
No, you said trigonometry.
No, no, no trigonometry.
No trigonometry.
You probably had geometry and algebra.
I got trigonometry in college, yeah.
What were the subjects you disliked the most?
History.
Studying Macbeth and all these.
these things related to English.
English literature, then.
Yeah, that's right.
And it shouldn't have been.
I regret that because, you know, that's pretty basic.
But I'm told that's a shortcoming of most engineers.
Do you think that's true?
A lot of them I've seen.
Could you explain the shortcoming?
No, I couldn't.
Unless...
unless it's difficult to have an across-the-board interest in high school subjects.
And I guess, I don't know whether it's math-inclined people migrate toward the engineers or vice versa, but I just couldn't find the interest in English and literature courses
Most of the girls did.
What about when you got to A&M in college?
You had them.
They were tough.
And I know it's just because I didn't apply myself to them I'm sure because you know the things you're interested in you work harder at.
I was sure glad when I got those things behind me in college.
Now I've heard that too and I teach a bunch of engineers

so what do you think about this idea that you find that true well this is your interview no i don't necessarily find that true but uh do you think it really is i mean is this do you think that's a general theme is that one of your attitudes that you think that engineers do have sort of a shortcoming when it comes to the liberal arts well let me let me put it this way i have
I have run into so many engineers who could not write a good letter and who could not do too well at speaking.
So I have just gone back to my own dislike for the English and English literature and things and thought they must have really had sort of the same lack of interest that I had.
You know, I'm just surmising that, but I do know that it's a sort of an accepted fact that engineers do not do too well in writing and being able to write and dictate letters and this sort of thing.
What type of student do you think you were in high school, junior high school, that age bracket?
And this is not to be bragging, but I was above average student I think.
I can look back and relate to my classmates and I think I was, I probably was in the, well maybe the top 20% or something.
Were you an outgoing student?
Were you in a lot of activities or what kind of activities?
Well I took part in all the sports and I declaimed several years in the interscholastic league meets.
I had one or two extemporaneous speech courses and some of that type thing.
I took agriculture in high school to get a little feel of the farm that I came off of.
So I didn't just take the things that I had to take.
I participated in a great many extracurricular activities.
Would you consider yourself, looking back at high school now, would you consider yourself being a person who was popular in high school?
Oh, yeah, I believe so.
I was, I know I was well thought of by the teachers.
Why is that?
Why do you know?
I mean, why did they think well of you?
Well, I think you know when they do.
I've had, you know, I've known a lot of them in subsequent years.
Some of them came back to the area to visit.
Well, why did they like you?
Maybe it was because I was a good student.
I don't know.
And I tried to get along with my fellow man.
I did participate in sports.
I participated in things that made them look good and made me look good.
I know I got along well with my...

fellow students because I was oh you know you'd play baseball and used to choose sides you know I'd get chosen early if you were going to take part in some of the competitive sports so they would ask me to do various things you know it I think I think you know
You know when you're an outcast, and you know also when you're... Later in life, of course, you became a leader.
Were you a leader in high school?
Were you the president of your student body, or anything like that, or a leader of any clubs?
Not really.
I tried to excel in what I did.
I was not trying to be on top of everything that came along, but anything that I took part in, I tried to do a good job of it.
In the first place, we didn't have a lot of the things that you mentioned in our school because it was a little rural school, but we did have the various things like the sport teams and the

reading and the math quizzes and spelling bees and all these sort of things but not not really the student bodies and all these sort of things they're they're they've come along since that guy but i uh i was uh oh i guess i was a sub leader i wasn't one that always hung back and waited for everybody else to do something
When you graduated from high school, it seems from what you've said that you had firm aims and firm goals.
You were a graduate right in the midst of the Depression.
Did that worry you at all?
No, it really didn't because I- In other words, you were an optimist.
You were an optimist even though we were in the middle of the Great Depression.
Well, actually I had never

up to that time I had not I was not the breadwinner I hadn't had to make my living okay yeah all right so even though I knew a nickel was hard to come by and I had worked some on Saturdays in a little store there we'd have to make a little change that I could call my own because my dad
If I asked him for a nickel, it'd be like asking you for a thousand dollars.
I remember asking him one time, and he said, boy, if I had a nickel, I'd buy some food with it.
So he had it just that tight.
That's what he said to me.
That's right, that's what he said to me.
And he made it.
He would give me a nickel, he'd have it to spare, but boy, a nickel at that time was big money.
And that seems, that's hard for some of the young ones to realize.
But after my dad said, I'll give you a place to sleep, I'll feed you, my mother made me a lunch.
I took a lunch every day I went to A&M.
Carried it with me.
He said he'd give me food and a place to stay, and my grandfather said, I'll let you use the car.
I said, all right, I'm going to school.
I got this little job on the campus making these $12 a month, and I knew right then that I was gonna make it.
If, because if I hadn't showed up for that job sometime there was four other people
They wanted it.
How'd you get that job?
Well, I lived poor.
What was that?
Well, there was a fellow by the name of Hensling that was head of the Landscape Art Department.
Hensel, Fritz Hensel.
H-E-N-S-E-L?
That's right.
Is that what the street is named after?
That's right.
That's right.
He was head of the Landscape Department for many years and my daddy's sister

was a good friend of his and worked somewhere out there at the university and she told him that I was out there and really needed a job and if he had anything that he could provide that she knew that I'd appreciate it and she would and I got a job.
Of course I had applied and
Tell them how much I did need it, but I had a little help.
I didn't just walk into it because, I'm not kidding you, there were six people for every job.
In other words, would you consider your family impoverished during the Depression?
Probably not in the term that you're describing it.
We never did.
Poor?
Oh, yes.
They were poor.

But people that lived on the farm were in better shape than people who didn't live on the farm because we killed our own beef, and that didn't really cost us anything because they ate the grass on the land.
We had a garden.
We raised our potatoes.
We had to buy beans and flour.
We ground our own corn and raised it.
They bought coffee.
And that's about it.
So we were never, we were never without something to eat.
But we didn't have anything to go to the picture show.
We didn't have anything to, you know, spend foolishly at all.
We had the clothes we needed.
Sometimes they had a lot of patches on them.
But we were not, even in the sense of some people today that are poverty-stricken, we were not, but we were poor.
How did the Depression and any of the New Deal programs, like the CCCs or the WPA, did they, did anyone in your family apply for any of those?
Did my immediate family?
No.
How about any of your relatives, were any of those people helped?
through any of the New Deal programs?
Oh, I'm sure there were.
Right off, I'm not, you know, I couldn't pinpoint which one, but not my immediate family.
Now, we were, I'm sure we got some of the agriculture assistance, whatever, but I don't specifically remember.
We had a farm, and we were, even though some of it was self-reported.
That's correct.
but like the CCC and I was I was real familiar with that and I don't know of any of our people that did.
Of course I was not a candidate because I was going to start school.
Now you still had sharecroppers on the farm at this time.
That's right.
How were they getting along?
Well they had it tough too and I'm sure there were a good many of them that my father and grandfather would

provide this food for and at the end of the year they didn't have enough to pay for it I expect, so I'm sure they owed them money that they never got, but they had it of course tougher than we, but it was an experience.
Did you ever, when you were growing up, did you ever go out to any of the sharecropper cabins and talk to any of them?
Oh yeah, lots of times.
In fact, we had a colored lady that lived in the backyard.
She had a house that worked for my grandfather.
It was as best I could relate back to his almost like slave times.
She lived right there in that house.
She worked for him and his wife was an invalid for many years and she cooked and cleaned up and kept the house and did whatever needed to be done and lived right there in the yard in a log cabin.
Many, many nights we'd go out and lay on her porch and talk to her and let her, she'd entertain us and jack with us and run us off when she got tired of us.
You know, this type of thing.
But we, gosh, we visited those folks and built the field and worked, you know, a little bit with them, pick a little cotton.
Didn't have to, but did and just, and we learned a great deal about them.
We went swimming with them.
I mean, we, there's,
The big ol' boys would take us swimming and just have the creek get run through the place.
So we were very close to them.
You said you learned a great deal from them.
What did you learn?
Could you be a little bit more specific?
Well, some of the basic things, lots of, I guess you'd say lots of philosophies of poor people.
I think that's a learning process.
You saw a complete different lifestyle that we lived.
You saw a complete different philosophy of life.
They, I don't think they ever expected to have anything much.
But they had a family and they had a somewhat of closeness that was different than ours.
So I learned a lot of
I guess I'd say I learned a lot of things that I'm glad I didn't have.

I learned a lot of things that you see people that are real close to the soil and real close to are a long way from being the educational levels that we had and I think it gave you more of an appreciation of what you had and were.
So this is the kind of things I think we learned.
Getting back to the Great Depression for a minute, for a minute, did this, did the Depression and the New Deal affect your thinking about politics?
Did you ever discuss politics?
Not really.
You didn't discuss politics with your father or anything?
What political persuasion was he?
Oh, he, I guess you'd say, I don't guess he ever voted anything but Democratic, but I don't think he's one of these that said, you know,
I'm a Democrat, my grandfather's a Democrat.
That was just sort of the philosophy of the land man.
But of course he died in 1952, so that wasn't long after Roosevelt had died, so he didn't have an opportunity to vote for others very much.
But he was a Roosevelt man basically?
Oh yeah, I'm sure he was.
But I expect, and I don't know about my grandfather because I was not really old enough to think about politics and besides that, you know, we had very limited radio.
We had a radio.
Did you have any electricity on it back in the 30s?
From 1936.
You did after 36.
I started A&M studying by kerosene lamp.
And after 36, the Bryan REA went through the area.
But up until that time, we did not have electricity.
But I studied my freshman year in Amherst.
You can do it.
I didn't know any better.
There's a well.
That's right.
I had to have a life.
And that was it.
They had had some ingenious lighting adaptations.
Somebody sold them over years ago on a carbide lighting system.
They had a big pit in the ground where this carbide dripped, I mean, dropped into water.
It was an automatic system that

carbide would drop into the water and make gas just like carbide is made now and then it was piped into the houses in a little small pipe and it actually burned and they had it mounted just like a light and you'd strike a match to it and the little carbide was burned made a beautiful little light it was pretty expensive to operate but that was a sort of ingenious system
but although we didn't have electricity, we had a nice refrigerator that ran off kerosene, it was Cervell, they were one of the early makers.
So it's, I've seen lots of changes for the good.
If you had to summarize those early years before you went off to hand out, summarize the themes of those years, how would you do that?
Oh I'm really what uh what vein are you thinking or I mean what uh well what were the important things in your early years?
I haven't really thought about that of course uh looking back on it I can think of a lot of things that are important I like the
Growing up on the farm was important.
I think it gave me a lot of basic roots that I wouldn't take far.
The chores that we had to do.
Of course my graduating, being able to graduate from high school with reasonably high honors, which gave me a lot of satisfaction.
The fact that my father and mother were able to raise all of us and come through the Depression without some sort of total collapse, I think I was grateful for.
The years that I look back on this experience of highway building that were early with me, I still have a great

interest in those years those teams pulling those scrapers watching drive piling for bridges with a big old hammer that they'd pull up and turn it loose and drop it you know nowadays they got steam and electricity that type of looking back is really interesting to me.
But probably the highlight was my being accepted to A&M as a freshman student over lots of turmoils and lots of things.
I got the letter saying I was accepted and I was really excited.
I know that you didn't have the money probably to go any other place, but did you ever consider any other alternatives besides A&M?
No.
It was basically then a question of this is a good engineering school and also finances.
That's right.
Those were considerations then?
Well, of course.
and and I never I never even thought about any other but looking back as of now I don't believe I would have been interested in going anywhere else anyhow.
Why not?
Well it's just my dad had had taken me many times to the campus by for

livestock you know take him to the vet school sure there were no veterinarians he had to have anything like that done with the vet school I used to go to horse shows with him out there they used to have horse shows where they had trotters and saddle gates and all this and the school just fascinated me the physical layout was interesting and of course

I'd never been to others I mean I had seen them but I'm not sure I would have been interested in going anywhere else but those two things engineering and of course the financial ability to go there and nowhere else.

Now you're a brigadier general did you ever consider West Point or any service school and in other words in your decision to go to college there was there was no thought about the military that did not come into your
Other than the fact that I was I was truly interested in ROTC.
I got I got I had a lot of interest in ROTC and I think if it had been optional at the time I went I'd have taken it.
It was not but I think I would have taken it.
Okay let's talk about the Corps.
Do you remember your first impressions of the Corps?
Yeah uh I
And I guess this is the first thing I thought.
Of course, the people I ran into were more juniors and seniors than anybody else because I was a day student.
And mainly my association with the Corps was on drill days.
But I remember the first thinking was, gosh, I don't know how they learned all this stuff.
And here I don't know anything about it.
And I felt lost, you know, because I drill twice a week.
And that was, of course, with the military with what we call the bull tags, you know, the military classroom work we had once a week, twice, whatever.
But my first impression with it was, you know, maybe I did the right thing, maybe I didn't.
I don't know whether I'll ever learn what all these juniors and seniors know about military and the like, but that kind of thing comes around pretty quickly.
But I did, I enjoyed it.
I liked to wear the uniform.
That intrigued me from the very beginning.
Why?
I don't know.
I like to have my uniform clean.
I like for it to be dressy looking and there was just something about a uniform to me that made you feel like you're one of them.
You were like a lot of other people and I have always liked group action.
